  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div xml:id="NA3-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu muṉṉoru kālattup poruḷvayiṉ pirinta talaimakaṉ piṉṉum poruḷ kaṭaikkūṭṭiya neñciṟkuc colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what HE, who had separated for the sake of wealth at an earlier time, [now] said to [his] heart that again coveted wealth.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA3">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            īṉparun tuyavum vāṉporu neṭuñciṉaip</l>
<l>            poriyarai vēmpiṉ puḷḷi nīḻaṟ</l>
<l>            kaṭṭaḷai yaṉṉa vaṭṭaraṅ kiḻaittuk </l>
<l>            kallāc ciṟāar nellivaṭ ṭāṭum</l>
<l>            villē ruḻavar vemmuṉaic cīṟūrc </l>
<l>            curaṉmutal vanta vuraṉmāy mālai</l>
<l>            yuḷḷiṉe ṉallaṉō yāṉē yuḷḷiya</l>
<l>            viṉaimuṭit taṉṉa viṉiyōṇ</l>
<l>            maṉaimāṇ cuṭaroṭu paṭarpoḻu teṉavē.</l>

        </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
         <l>Strength-vanquishing evening, come onto the desert,</l>
         <l>in a little village, a hot battle-front for ploughmen</l>
         <l rend="indent3">[who have] bows for ploughs,<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">vil ēr uḻavar</term>: this is a standard metaphor for plunderers who "plough", i.e. earn their livelihood, with their bow, robbing travellers (cf. AN 193.2). Similar topoi exist in connection with the fishermen, who harvest the sea or the salt-fields without ploughing (cf. NA 254.11f., 331.1f., AN 140.2), or with the king who ploughs with his sword (cf. PN 368.13, 371.14).</note> </l>
         <l rend="indent">where the untaught children play with Nelli [fruits] for pawns,</l>
        <l rend="indent">having made a play-field with pawns<note place="foot">The variant <term xml:lang="ta">iṭṭu</term> is slightly more tricky: "having made a play-field set up as if with touchstones"(?)</note> like a touchstone<note place="foot">The touchstone looks black and gold like golden Nelli fruit on dark soil (cf. KT 67).</note>,</l>
        <l rend="indent2">in the dappled shade of a Neem tree with parched base [and]</l>
        <l rend="indent2">sky-touching long branches, where a kite in labour is suffering</l>
        <l>− I still remember<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">uḷḷiṉeṉ</term> can be understood as a p.a. in aoristic function, i.e. an action already begun and still going on.</note> [it], don't I?, thinking</l>
        <l rend="indent">[this is] the time of affliction, with glorious light in the house,</l>
	    <l rend="indent2">for her who is sweet like a fulfilled task one looks back on.”</l>

         
        </lg>
        
      </div>
